European inflation has slipped into food
The accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dizzying increase in food prices.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 per cent of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent - announced the EU Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely to give 3 percent - the Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, together with the increasing prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "trade" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, registered in Germany, beat the record by twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation took place in the euro area as a result of the massive food and energy prices.
End-of-wheat contributions increased by 88 per cent and so did soybean contributions reach their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and milk products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching the black gold by almost $100 per barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 per cent current to 2.5 per cent, but by 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
Gallup foresees a government crisis
After a long stagnation, by early December the support of the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its maximum level since 2002, while the Gallup had never experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of the socialists.
The difference in the case of safe party voters - due to the greater firmness of opposition voters - would mean support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of one-fifth for socialists (20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach the necessary limit to have any parliamentary seats: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the safe voters there is one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the lowest point - it has never been so high, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believes that the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As regards next year, the majority of the population is experiencing deterioration and only one-tenth of the population expects improvement.
In December, 71 per cent of the respondents, more than any previous Gallup survey, felt that the President of Government was doing something wrong than his duties.
13 percent of the consultants trust or rely heavily on Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of the consultants.
54 per cent of the population did not trust the Head of Government at all and 27 per cent did not trust the President of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators for shaping the political situation is that, what proportion of society believes it is possible to control the discontent experienced against the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year, 35 per cent felt it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, this proportion is currently only 20 per cent, while the relative majority (33 per cent) believes that the only solution is the holding of new elections.
The interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 per cent of respondents to the question about participation responded that it would certainly participate and another 20 per cent said that it is likely to participate.
Comparatively, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" only 55 per cent of the population would participate safely, and another 15 per cent believed likely their participation. Based on current voters' intentions there is no doubt of the result of the popular consultation.
74 per cent of the population would disapprove of the payment of study fees, 79 per cent of the medical consultation service and 84 per cent of hospital care.
If we observe these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of the voters would reject the introduction of study rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has fivefolded its prices
They maintained the average price increase of 16 percent of Budaörs' gold trade triangle hypermarkets, with the difference that VAT has not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the Budaörs gold trade triangle the usual Christmas basket of the Napi newspaper, but in all hypermarkets there was a much higher growth than the thousand HUF.
As in December last year prices in food supermarkets had already "disappeared" so there was no drastic increase in percentage compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what last year was able to buy at a price well below the 9,000 HUF, today they cannot even buy for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the studied hypermarkets exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10 573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a strong increase in turkey breast fillet, nut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in Auchan we also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was equally surprising in this shop that the price of Coca-Cola with two-litre redeemable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in the basket of Napi Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our estimates, with respect to last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan by about 18 percent the prices in the basket of Napi.
Comparing the most expensive basket values last year with the cheapest basket this year, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between the cheapest last year and the most expensive this year has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during last year's Christmas in prices there was an increase in VAT.
This process was precisely the one that destroyed trade, supermarkets visibly were unable to decide on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of price change on consumption.
(If the trader plans the speed of movement of a product poorly, he may lose an important benefit on the margin that is adjusted to the volume of sales.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, which the most expensive was 1720 HUF to the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only of 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, as the highest price of today has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest has also increased by 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic increase in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets more than 30 percent the price of consumer items of first-needed consumption grew.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some food of first need, recorded a price increase of more than 30 per cent in the 12-month period.
