However, we have information that domestic sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to polling institutes because income is below their plans and not only in the case of food but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals it saves with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been reported in hospitals primarily due to the improper application of antibiotics.
The circumstances of hygiene prevailing in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overburdening of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the chief doctor of the department of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a contagion with MRSA has been diagnosed in the trauma department of Hospital János.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital early in the year.
A wound in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient shortly after had to return to the hospital as a result of the MRSA infection and since then there has been no significant surgical intervention by the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10, this year, there have been cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance 1094 - said Karolina Böröcz, department doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that the number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded in hospitals, and there is no information.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methylin-oxacylin.
One third of humans carry in their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. inflammation of the throat, amygdalitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once excessively or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become very antibiotic-resistant bacteria and quickly become infected in inadequate hospital conditions.
They may cause serious hospital infections, such as injuries or septicemia first of all to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with weakened body, elderly or low weight individuals.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of Hospital János there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection with the epidemic should not be confused, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic-resistant
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff cares for them in rubber gloves and masks and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but it is not even possible to prevent infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of training and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA.
However, in Hungarian hospitals microbiological sampling is not fashionable.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most of the cases come into public light when the infections of MRSA are already visible in the patient - said the department doctor-head of the epidemiological center.
The European Union strongly commends the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological tables.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is directed, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent resistance to medicines, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples is even less frequent in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
It saves itself with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, they play a very important role in hand-washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks, but also in this sense there are significant shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is infected through drop transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated for at least a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - Karolina Böröcz added - that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation saves themselves with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate prevention measures are carried out, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of disease with MRSA is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is being fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program appears to have success, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
