EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
The Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and the Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements worth EUR 400 million on Friday in Budapest to finance education, transport and the environment infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance projects for transport and environmental protection in the Hungarian budget, which will be financed from cohesion funds, of which the parties had already signed a credit contract worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit contract is also used to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this Hungarian objective, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken later by extending the credit contract.
The parties signed a contract for €50 million for innovations, which the budget will employ primarily for the University of Debrecen innovation and research project.
During the discussions they also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalises with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will again address the issue that if it is necessary or not modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the appropriations is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charge for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
