Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, meetings at the expert level will be completed on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at the ministerial level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world discuss the Bali Roadmap, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, established in the Kyoto Protocol, which was in force until 2012.
Discussions are currently taking place on the particular issue between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures for the time being, although it tends to agree that compared to the 1990 situation, by 2020 the emission of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether the industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are prepared to provide material and technological assistance to countries that need it.
An agreement was also reached on aid for developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be headed by a steering board consisting of 16 members, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes "Piac è Profit".
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020, regardless of whether or not the "after 2012 agreement" will be signed and is willing to commit to reducing even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and the developing countries are also willing to undertake commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed themselves to decrease by 5.2 per cent, including 15 EU Member States then committed to reaching 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce by 6 per cent the greenhouse gas emissions for the period 1985-87, which our country will fulfil - notes the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
This is a great deal of what is at stake in Bali, since within two years the international climate policy agreement will have to be signed in the long term, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments, as assumed in the Kyoto Protocol, would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, which was called upon in its most recent report by the IPCC, an international scientific association of the United Nations that deals with climate change, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would result in a delay in reducing emissions and could not prevent an increase of more than 2°C of the earth's average temperature, which according to scientists would have irreversible and immeasurable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish footage of filmed actions in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: the special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban - reported the BBC.
These tapes made with mini cameras mounted on helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general operating body, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
Political message is inevitable
Already there are 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been loaded to the Internet in this way and their "channel" has already been seen by over 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in spring 2007 as "headquarters defence" and publishes videos of actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Community Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment objectives, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence, they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots - told the BBC the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - on the other hand, inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for being of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned that, in addition to the carefully edited and censored recordings, amateur videos appear in the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers speak at most of the losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army has only recently taken advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with videogames of shootings, free downloadable, called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly instead of the soldiers.
