A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitlerian regime, are at liberty.
The 47 million file documents, stored over 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far accessible only for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and nominally, at the request of an old victim or his right-wing.
The eleven States responsible for their management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to the researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has ended, openness has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
Access by historians to Bad Arolsen will allow searches " particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced workers " , explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, opposed the opening of these nominative documents to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
Records of the concentration camps or detention orders established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the peasants deported or subjected to compulsory work and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their detention, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual petitions.
