Congress approves the transposition of Mifid, which entered into force 1 November
In parallel with its parliamentary procedure, which ended today with the Congress voting on amendments incorporated into the draft Senate, the Government has submitted to the public hearing the rules of procedure for the development of the new law, with the aim of both to come into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by deputies and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulation in order to ensure investor protection and to regulate in detail the activity of the entities so that markets operate efficiently.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, requires the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (NCMV) and promotes cooperation between the various European Union supervisors.
The new regulation will provide financial advisory services to both specialized firms and natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial services (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFI), which join value companies, securities agencies and portfolio managers.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the implementation of financial instrument operations, so that regulated secondary markets are complemented by multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment service companies to disclose on the market information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management and requires them to keep a record of all the operations they perform, to facilitate NCMV monitoring.
In its passage by the Committee on the Economy of Congress, several amendments were incorporated, including the fact that the debt securities are considered as a "complex" financial instrument given its high risk to the investor, which has been demonstrated by the debt of high-risk mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally define the functions that may be performed by graduates in Economics and Business 30 years after the adoption of the Royal Decree defining the professional functions reserved for economists in 1977.
For its part, the Senate has incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as that of the mediator, who will work on behalf of others, will not require the authorization of the CNMV and will be able to provide its product marketing and customer collection services to different investment companies at the same time.
